    "body": "### Problem\n\nusing neovim 0.12.\n\nwith\n\n```\nsyntax on\nset noeol\nset nofixeol\n```\n\ni would expect the same behaviour as\n\n```\nset noeol\nset nofixeol\nsyntax on\n```\n\nsadly that's some times not the case. opening a file which ends with a newline, the latter is removed when the file name has certain suffixes (checked `.md`, `.lua`), while for a file which does not end in one of those suffixes, the newline is left in peace as is expected.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```\nprintf 'syntax on\\nset noeol\\nset nofixendofline\\n' > /tmp/min.vim\nprintf 'foo\\n' > /tmp/t2.md\nprintf 'foo\\n' > /tmp/t2\nnvim -u /tmp/min.vim --noplugin --headless '+set eol?' '+q!' /tmp/t2.md\necho\nnvim -u /tmp/min.vim --noplugin --headless '+set eol?' '+q!' /tmp/t2\necho\n```\n\noutput is\n\n```\nnoendofline\n  endofline\n```\n\n\n\nnow, moving the syntax line last:\n```\nprintf 'set noeol\\nset nofixendofline\\nsyntax on\\n' > /tmp/min.vim\nprintf 'foo\\n' > /tmp/t2.md\nprintf 'foo\\n' > /tmp/t2\nnvim -u /tmp/min.vim --noplugin --headless '+set eol?' '+q!' /tmp/t2.md\necho\nnvim -u /tmp/min.vim --noplugin --headless '+set eol?' '+q!' /tmp/t2\necho\n```\n\nthe output is \n```\n  endofline\n  endofline\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\ni expect it not to matter where in the init file `syntax on` is. for the example/reproducer above, i'd expect `endofline` for both cases.\n\nmy intention with `set noeol` and `set nofixeol` is that new files don't get a newline and existing ones retain the current state.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.12.2 Build type: Release LuaJIT 2.1.1774896198 Run \"nvim -V1 -v\" for more info\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, not seen this in vim *ever*, confirmed with 9.1 just now\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS 26.5.1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nTerminal.app Version 2.15 (470.2)\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nscreen-256color  (inside tmux 3.6), but behaves the same in bare Terminal.app (xterm-256colour)\n\n### Installation\n\nmacports",
