            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> > that new files don't get a newline and existing ones retain the current state.\n> \n> I think you should use `:setglobal` instead of `:set`.\n\nthank you for looking into this. may i ask why this would be the better setting?\ndoesn't `set` set the value both, locally and globally?\n\nfrom the help:\n```\nFor buffer-local and window-local options:\n        Command          global value     local value          condition\n      :set option=value      set              set\n :setlocal option=value       -               set\n:setglobal option=value      set               -\n\n```\n\nor, were you suggesting that they shouldn't be in effect locally?  (if so: why?)\n\n\nre-testing it with setglobal:\n\n```\nprintf 'syntax on\\nsetglobal noeol\\nsetglobal nofixendofline\\n' > /tmp/min.vim\nprintf 'foo\\n' > /tmp/t2.md\nprintf 'foo\\n' > /tmp/t2\nnvim -u /tmp/min.vim --noplugin --headless '+set eol?' '+q!' /tmp/t2.md\necho\nnvim -u /tmp/min.vim --noplugin --headless '+set eol?' '+q!' /tmp/t2\necho\n```\n\nit seems that this indeed does not change the line ending.\n\ni see 2 problems with it, though:\n\n1. it doesn't explain why this only affects markdown files\n2. it doesn't explain why the ordering changes the settings\n3. it fails a different one of my requirements: when creating a new file without a \\n at the end, it silently adds one (not sure i'm driving it the correct way but reproduced manually as well):\n ```\nprintf 'syntax on\\nsetglobal noeol\\nsetglobal nofixendofline\\n' > /tmp/min.vim\nnvim -u /tmp/min.vim --noplugin --headless -c 'call feedkeys(\"ifoo\\<Esc>:wq\\<CR>\", \"x\")' /tmp/foo_no_nl\nxxd /tmp/foo_no_nl\n```\n\nyields \n\n```\n00000000: 666f 6f0a                                foo.\n```\n\nso, it added a newline, which i didn't want.",
